Part c (3 points)

Create a new list that contains elements corresponding to each playerâs points_per_game.

  • points_per_game = points/games_played

Name each element with the respective playerâs initials.

ie: The first element of the list will be 33.44693 and the name of this element will be MJ.

Hint: initialize an empty list

Note: this must still run correctly even if the values were to change or if another player were added to the list or if the player order changed.

# initializing list 
player_points_pg <- list()

for (i in 1:length(player_info)) {
  
  # appending points per game
  ppg <- player_info[[i]]$points / player_info[[i]]$games_played
  player_points_pg <- append(player_points_pg, ppg)
}

# applying names to new list  
names(player_points_pg) <- c(names(player_info))

# print 
print(player_points_pg)

Question 3 (3 points)

Consider the matrix mat_rand of random numbers below.

rand_num <- c(sample(10:100, 10), sample(100:999, 10), sample(1000:2000, 10))

mat_rand <- matrix(sample(rand_num, 30), ncol = 5)

Use an appropriate apply function to round values with 2 digits to the nearest tens, values with 3 digits to the nearest hundreds, and 4 digits to the nearest thousands.

ie: 91 rounds to 90; 173 rounds to 200; 1450 rounds to 1000

Hint: use MARGIN = 1:2 to apply the function to each value instead of only a row/col.

# takes number and boils it down to a value of 1 with decimals 
# by dividing it by 10, 100, 1000, or however big the number is 
# rounds, then brings number back up

round_to <- function(x) {
  val <- round(x / (10^(nchar(x) - 1))) * (10^(nchar(x) - 1)) 
}

apply(mat_rand, MARGIN = 1:2, round_to)
     [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4] [,5]

Part c (5 points)

Calculate the median annual temperature for your Colorado data set.

Use the which.max() and which.min() function to determine which year had the highest median temperature and which year had the lowest median temperature.

Then print the sentence:

âThe maximum median annual temperature of {} occurred in {} and the minimum median annual temperature of {} occurred in {}.â

Example (this is NOT the answer just an example of what goes in the {}):

âThe maximum median annual temperature of 68.25 occurred in 2017 and the minimum median annual temperature of 57.15 occurred in 1907.â

Note: This code should still run successfully even if the numbers were to change.

# initializing vector 
median_year <- c()

for (i in 1:nrow(co_df)) {
  
  # collecting median per year 
  median_val <- median(as.numeric(co_df[i, 3:12]))
  median_year <- append(median_year, median_val)
  
  # min and max indexes (index will equal same for median_year & co_df)
  max_t <- which.max(median_year)
  min_t <- which.min(median_year)
}

# print statement 
print(paste0('The maximum median annual temperature of ', median_year[max_t], ' occurred in ', co_df[max_t, 'year'], ' and the minimum median annual temperature of ', median_year[min_t], ' occurred in ', co_df[min_t, 'year'], '.'))

Question 5 (5 points)

Write a recursive function that calculates the sum of the digits in a number.

Example: The number 312 would return 6 (3 + 1 + 2)

Run your function with 935068.

odd_num_char <- function(x) {
  # base case; nchar == 1
  if (nchar(x) == 1) {
    return(x)
  }
  
  # recursive case 
  return((x %/% (10^(nchar(x) - 1)) + odd_num_char(as.numeric(substring(x, 2)))))
  
  }

odd_num_char(935068)
[1] 31
